recordings.loc: Sand Canyon, Santa Clarita, Los Angeles County, California
recordings.rmk: The hawk was very visible and looked like a younger adult from the size and plumage; it had greyer wings and a greyer head than usual, while the chest featured a mix of white and brown colors on the feathers. It was perched and calling from a high, naked branch of a coast live oak (Quercus agrifolia) which was near a street (Tannahill Ave). The surrounding area is a dry, coast live oak grove filled with various small songbirds, mourning doves, crows, and woodpeckers.  The hawk was getting lightly mobbed by crows while we were there, and it took the crows quite a bit of time to eventually chase the hawk away.

Houston, Harris County, Texas
recordings.rmk:
This bird is heard calling outside of my apartment in Houston daily, usually in the morning. I've never seen it. It sits in the canopy of a tree among many trees in a schoolyard. 

I have not altered the timbre of the recording, other than using a high-pass filter to remove low hum from a nearby air conditioning unit. Each call was originally about a minute apart, but I cropped the recording to condense the calls.

I am a composer of electroacoustic music and am using this recording in a new work. I would love to know what kind of bird this is!

I believe this to be a Red-shouldered Hawk but did not see the bird.  I had a Blue Jay doing an imitation of this bird about a mile away from where I heard this one yesterday.  This sounds more like a Red-shouldered to me due to how loud it was as well as the descending note at the end.

Thanks
